  <h1>Mulch Calculator</h1>
  <p class="page-desc">Calculate the cubic yards, bags, weight, and cost of mulch, gravel, topsoil, sand, or compost for your landscaping project.</p>

  <div class="calculator-box">
    <div class="calc-inputs">
      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="areaLength">Area Length (ft)</label>
        <input type="number" id="areaLength" value="20" min="0" step="0.1" />
      </div>
      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="areaWidth">Area Width (ft)</label>
        <input type="number" id="areaWidth" value="10" min="0" step="0.1" />
      </div>
      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="desiredDepth">Desired Depth (inches)</label>
        <input type="number" id="desiredDepth" value="3" min="0.5" step="0.5" />
      </div>
      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="materialType">Material Type</label>
        <select id="materialType">
          <option value="mulch" selected>Mulch</option>
          <option value="gravel">Gravel</option>
          <option value="topsoil">Topsoil</option>
          <option value="sand">Sand</option>
          <option value="compost">Compost</option>
        </select>
      </div>
      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="pricePerYard">Price per Cubic Yard ($)</label>
        <input type="number" id="pricePerYard" value="35" min="0" step="0.01" />
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="calc-results">
      <div class="result-cards">
        <div class="result-card primary">
          <span class="result-label">Cubic Yards</span>
          <span class="result-value" id="resultCubicYards">1.85</span>
        </div>
        <div class="result-card">
          <span class="result-label">Cubic Feet</span>
          <span class="result-value" id="resultCubicFeet">50.00</span>
        </div>
        <div class="result-card">
          <span class="result-label">2-Cu-Ft Bags</span>
          <span class="result-value" id="resultBags">25</span>
        </div>
        <div class="result-card">
          <span class="result-label">Estimated Weight</span>
          <span class="result-value" id="resultWeight">1,111 lbs</span>
        </div>
        <div class="result-card success">
          <span class="result-label">Estimated Cost</span>
          <span class="result-value" id="resultCost">$64.81</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <AdUnit slot="calc-mid" format="rectangle" />

  <article class="content-section">
    <h2>How to Calculate Mulch for Your Yard</h2>
    <p>Calculating the right amount of mulch or landscaping material saves you money and multiple trips to the garden center. Whether you are mulching flower beds, filling raised garden beds with topsoil, or laying gravel for a walkway, the formula is the same: multiply the area by the desired depth and convert to the appropriate unit of measurement.</p>
    <p>The standard unit for bulk landscaping materials in the United States is the cubic yard. One cubic yard is a volume of material that is 3 feet long, 3 feet wide, and 3 feet deep, equaling 27 cubic feet. Bagged products are typically sold in 2-cubic-foot bags at home improvement stores, though some premium mulches come in 1.5-cubic-foot bags.</p>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <code>Cubic Yards = (Length &times; Width &times; Depth in feet) / 27</code>
    </div>
    <p>Start by measuring the length and width of the area in feet. If the area is not a simple rectangle, break it into smaller rectangular or circular sections, calculate each one separately, and add the volumes together. Next, decide on the desired depth. Most mulch applications call for 2 to 4 inches of material. Convert the depth from inches to feet by dividing by 12. Multiply the length by the width by the depth in feet to get cubic feet, then divide by 27 to convert to cubic yards.</p>
    <p>For example, a garden bed that is 20 feet long, 10 feet wide, and 3 inches deep requires 20 times 10 times 0.25 (3 inches divided by 12) equals 50 cubic feet, which is 50 divided by 27 equals 1.85 cubic yards. Rounding up, you would order 2 cubic yards of mulch or purchase 25 bags of 2-cubic-foot mulch.</p>

    <h2>Mulch Depth Guide by Application</h2>
    <p>The right mulch depth depends on the purpose of the mulch, the type of material, and the plants or landscape features it surrounds. Too little mulch fails to suppress weeds and retain moisture, while too much can suffocate plant roots and create conditions for fungal diseases.</p>
    <p><strong>Flower beds and perennial gardens (2-3 inches):</strong> Most annual and perennial gardens benefit from 2 to 3 inches of organic mulch such as shredded hardwood, bark chips, or cocoa hulls. This depth is sufficient to suppress most weeds, retain soil moisture, and moderate soil temperature. Avoid piling mulch against plant stems, which can cause rot.</p>
    <p><strong>Tree rings and shrub beds (3-4 inches):</strong> Around trees and shrubs, apply 3 to 4 inches of mulch in a ring extending at least 2 to 3 feet from the trunk. Keep mulch 3 to 6 inches away from the trunk itself to prevent moisture buildup that can cause bark decay and pest problems. The common practice of creating mulch volcanos piled against tree trunks is harmful and should be avoided.</p>
    <p><strong>Pathways and walkways (3-4 inches):</strong> For decorative mulch pathways, use 3 to 4 inches of material. Gravel or stone pathways may require a thicker layer of 4 to 6 inches, especially if you are laying the material over landscape fabric. A thicker layer prevents the underlying fabric or soil from showing through as foot traffic compresses the material.</p>
    <p><strong>Playground areas (6-12 inches):</strong> Safety surfaces under playground equipment require much deeper material. The Consumer Product Safety Commission recommends at least 9 inches of wood mulch or wood chips under equipment with a fall height up to 7 feet, and 12 inches for fall heights up to 10 feet. Engineered wood fiber (EWF) is the preferred material for playground surfaces.</p>
    <p><strong>Erosion control (4-6 inches):</strong> For slopes and areas prone to erosion, apply 4 to 6 inches of mulch. Shredded bark and hardwood mulch knit together better than chips or nuggets on slopes, reducing the chance of the material washing away during heavy rain. For steep slopes, consider using erosion control blankets in combination with mulch.</p>

    <h2>Mulch vs Gravel vs Topsoil</h2>
    <p>While the calculator works for multiple landscaping materials, each one has distinct properties, uses, and considerations. Choosing the right material for your project depends on the intended purpose, climate, maintenance preferences, and budget.</p>
    <p><strong>Mulch</strong> is an organic material made from shredded or chipped wood, bark, leaves, or other plant matter. It decomposes over time, adding nutrients to the soil and improving soil structure. This decomposition means mulch needs to be replenished every 1 to 2 years. Mulch is ideal for garden beds, tree rings, and any area where soil health matters. It suppresses weeds, retains soil moisture, insulates plant roots, and gives landscapes a polished appearance.</p>
    <p><strong>Gravel</strong> is an inorganic material that does not decompose, making it a permanent landscaping solution. It is ideal for driveways, walkways, drainage areas, and dry-climate landscapes where water conservation is a priority. Gravel comes in many sizes and colors, from pea gravel (3/8 inch) to river rock (1 to 3 inches). Because gravel is much heavier than mulch, delivery and handling costs are higher. One cubic yard of gravel weighs approximately 2,800 pounds, compared to 600 pounds for mulch.</p>
    <p><strong>Topsoil</strong> is a nutrient-rich soil used to fill raised beds, amend existing garden soil, level lawns, and establish new planting areas. It weighs about 2,200 pounds per cubic yard and is sold in bulk or in 40-pound bags. When ordering topsoil, look for a screened product free of rocks, roots, and debris. For raised bed gardens, consider a garden soil blend that mixes topsoil with compost and other amendments for optimal plant growth.</p>
    <p><strong>Sand</strong> is used for leveling paver installations, creating drainage layers, and amending clay soils. Play sand is used for sandboxes and recreational areas. Masonry sand is used as a setting bed for pavers and flagstone. Sand weighs approximately 2,700 pounds per cubic yard, making it one of the heaviest common landscaping materials.</p>
    <p><strong>Compost</strong> is fully decomposed organic matter used as a soil amendment. It improves soil structure, adds nutrients, and enhances moisture retention. Compost weighs about 1,000 pounds per cubic yard and is applied at 1 to 3 inches over existing soil or mixed into the top 6 to 12 inches of garden beds. For new lawns, a 1-inch layer of compost topdressing provides an excellent growing medium.</p>

    <h2>How Much Does Mulch Weigh?</h2>
    <p>The weight of landscaping materials varies significantly by type and moisture content. Knowing the weight is important for planning delivery logistics, ensuring your vehicle can handle the load, and estimating the physical effort required for the project.</p>
    <p><strong>Mulch</strong> weighs approximately 600 to 800 pounds per cubic yard, depending on the type and moisture content. Dry shredded hardwood mulch is on the lighter end at about 400 to 600 pounds per cubic yard, while wet or freshly chipped mulch can weigh 800 to 1,000 pounds per cubic yard. A standard pickup truck with a 6-foot bed can hold about 1 to 1.5 cubic yards of mulch.</p>
    <p><strong>Gravel</strong> is much heavier at 2,600 to 3,000 pounds per cubic yard depending on the stone type and size. Pea gravel and crushed limestone are on the lower end, while dense river rock and granite are on the upper end. A full-size pickup truck can safely haul about 1 cubic yard of gravel before exceeding payload limits.</p>
    <p><strong>Topsoil</strong> weighs 2,000 to 2,400 pounds per cubic yard depending on moisture content and composition. Wet topsoil is significantly heavier than dry. Screened topsoil with a high sand content will be heavier than organic-rich topsoil.</p>
    <p><strong>Sand</strong> weighs approximately 2,500 to 2,900 pounds per cubic yard. Wet sand can weigh up to 3,400 pounds per cubic yard because water fills the spaces between sand particles. Always confirm the weight capacity of your delivery vehicle before transporting sand.</p>
    <p><strong>Compost</strong> is the lightest bulk material at 800 to 1,200 pounds per cubic yard. Aged, dry compost is lighter, while fresh, wet compost is heavier. Compost is easy to handle but tends to be dusty when dry.</p>

    <h2>Bulk vs Bagged Mulch</h2>
    <p>One of the most common decisions homeowners face is whether to buy mulch in bulk or in bags. Both options have advantages and disadvantages depending on the size of your project, access to the work area, and your budget.</p>
    <p><strong>Bulk mulch</strong> is sold by the cubic yard and delivered by dump truck directly to your property. It is the most cost-effective option for large projects. Bulk mulch typically costs $20 to $50 per cubic yard depending on the type and your location, plus a delivery fee of $30 to $100. For a project requiring 5 or more cubic yards, bulk delivery saves significant money compared to buying bags.</p>
    <p><strong>Bagged mulch</strong> is sold in 2-cubic-foot bags at home improvement stores and garden centers. A bag typically costs $3 to $6, which translates to roughly $40 to $80 per cubic yard (13.5 bags per cubic yard times $3 to $6 per bag). Bagged mulch is more convenient for small projects, is easier to store, and can be transported in a standard car. It is also cleaner and more consistent in quality and appearance than some bulk products.</p>
    <p>The break-even point between bulk and bagged mulch is typically around 3 to 4 cubic yards. Below that volume, the convenience and lower delivery hassle of bags often outweighs the higher per-yard cost. Above that volume, bulk delivery is almost always more economical. One cubic yard of mulch equals about 13.5 bags of 2-cubic-foot mulch, so a 5-cubic-yard project would require nearly 68 bags, which is impractical to transport and handle.</p>
    <p>Consider access to the work area when choosing between bulk and bagged. Bulk mulch is dumped in a pile on your driveway or yard and must be moved by wheelbarrow. If the garden beds are far from the drop zone or if you need to navigate narrow gates or stairways, bags may be easier to handle even for larger projects.</p>

    <h2>Best Time to Apply Mulch</h2>
    <p>Timing your mulch application correctly maximizes its benefits and reduces the need for repeated applications throughout the year. The optimal time depends on your climate, the purpose of the mulch, and the types of plants in your landscape.</p>
    <p><strong>Spring (mid to late spring):</strong> The most popular time to apply mulch is in mid to late spring after the soil has warmed and spring rains have subsided. Applying mulch too early in spring can trap cold moisture in the soil and delay plant growth. Wait until perennials have emerged and the soil temperature reaches at least 60 degrees Fahrenheit. Spring mulching helps retain moisture through the summer heat, suppresses weed growth, and gives the landscape a fresh, clean appearance.</p>
    <p><strong>Fall (after first frost):</strong> A second mulch application in fall, after the first hard frost, helps insulate plant roots through the winter. This is especially important for newly planted trees and shrubs, perennial gardens, and areas with shallow-rooted plants. Fall mulch also prevents frost heaving, which can push plants out of the ground during freeze-thaw cycles.</p>
    <p><strong>Summer (as needed):</strong> If mulch has decomposed or thinned during the growing season, a light refresh in midsummer can restore coverage. Avoid applying thick layers during hot, humid weather, as this can create conditions favorable for fungal growth and pest problems.</p>
    <p>Most organic mulches need to be replenished every 12 to 18 months as they decompose. Hardwood mulch typically lasts longer than pine bark or pine straw. Cedar mulch is naturally resistant to decay and insect damage, making it one of the longest-lasting organic options. Rubber mulch and stone mulches last indefinitely but do not contribute to soil health.</p>

    <h2>Landscaping Material Cost Guide</h2>
    <p>The cost of landscaping materials varies by material type, quality, quantity, and regional availability. Below is a general pricing guide to help you budget your next landscaping project.</p>
    <p><strong>Mulch:</strong> $20 to $50 per cubic yard for bulk delivery. Premium mulches like cedar, cypress, and colored hardwood are on the higher end. Economy mulch and recycled wood mulch are on the lower end. Bagged mulch costs $3 to $6 per 2-cubic-foot bag.</p>
    <p><strong>Gravel and stone:</strong> $25 to $75 per cubic yard for bulk delivery. Pea gravel and crushed limestone are the most affordable. Decorative river rock, Mexican beach pebbles, and polished stone are more expensive. Delivery fees for gravel are often higher than for mulch due to the weight.</p>
    <p><strong>Topsoil:</strong> $15 to $40 per cubic yard for bulk screened topsoil. Garden soil blends with added compost and amendments cost $30 to $60 per cubic yard. Bagged topsoil costs $3 to $7 per 40-pound bag.</p>
    <p><strong>Sand:</strong> $20 to $45 per cubic yard for bulk sand. Play sand is typically $4 to $6 per 50-pound bag. Masonry sand costs slightly more than fill sand.</p>
    <p><strong>Compost:</strong> $25 to $55 per cubic yard for bulk compost. Bagged compost costs $4 to $8 per bag. Mushroom compost and specialty blends are on the higher end.</p>
    <p>Delivery fees typically range from $30 to $100 per load and may vary based on distance from the supplier. Some suppliers offer free delivery for orders above a minimum quantity, such as 5 cubic yards or more. Ordering multiple materials on the same delivery can sometimes reduce per-load fees.</p>
    <p>To minimize costs, compare prices from multiple local suppliers, check for seasonal sales in early spring and late fall, and consider splitting a bulk order with neighbors if your individual project is small. Municipal composting programs in many areas offer free or low-cost compost to residents.</p>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="faq-list">
  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>How many cubic yards of mulch do I need?</summary>
    <p>Multiply the area in square feet by the desired depth in feet, then divide by 27 to convert cubic feet to cubic yards. For example, a garden bed that is 500 square feet with a 3-inch mulch depth requires 500 times 0.25 (3 inches divided by 12) equals 125 cubic feet, divided by 27 equals 4.63 cubic yards. Round up to 5 cubic yards to ensure full coverage. One cubic yard of mulch covers approximately 162 square feet at 2 inches deep, 108 square feet at 3 inches deep, and 81 square feet at 4 inches deep. Use these coverage rates as a quick reference when estimating how much material to order.</p>
  </details>
  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>How much does a cubic yard of mulch cover?</summary>
    <p>One cubic yard of mulch covers different areas depending on the depth applied. At 1 inch deep, one cubic yard covers 324 square feet. At 2 inches deep, it covers 162 square feet. At 3 inches deep, it covers 108 square feet. At 4 inches deep, it covers 81 square feet. These coverage numbers apply to all loose-fill landscaping materials including mulch, gravel, topsoil, and compost. To calculate coverage, divide 324 by the depth in inches. For example, at 2.5 inches deep, one cubic yard covers 324 divided by 2.5 equals about 130 square feet.</p>
  </details>
  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>How many bags of mulch are in a cubic yard?</summary>
    <p>One cubic yard contains 27 cubic feet, so you need about 13.5 bags of 2-cubic-foot mulch to equal one cubic yard (27 divided by 2 equals 13.5). In practice, round up to 14 bags per cubic yard. Bulk mulch is almost always cheaper than bagged mulch on a per-cubic-yard basis. At $4 per bag, 13.5 bags cost $54 for one cubic yard of mulch, while bulk delivery of the same amount typically costs $25 to $45 plus a delivery fee. For projects requiring 3 or more cubic yards, bulk delivery usually offers the best value.</p>
  </details>
</div>
